SIMPLE: incivility
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Incivility
<hw>In`ci*vil"i*ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Incivilities</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>incivilitas</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incivilit⟦eacute⟧</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality or state of being uncivil; lack of
courtesy; rudeness of manner; impoliteness.</def> <rj><au>Shak.
Tillotson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any act of rudeness or ill breeding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Uncomely jests, loud talking and jeering, which, in civil account,
are called indecencies and <qex>incivilities</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer.
Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Lack of civilization; a state of rudeness or
barbarism.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir W. Raleigh.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Impoliteness; uncourteousness; unmannerliness;
disrespect; rudeness; discourtesy.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Incivilization</ent>⟦br⟧
